<body>
    <h1>Testing Microservices</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p></p>
<div class=3D"">
<div class=3D"childtabs-macro" data-fixed-position=3D"false">
<div class=3D"aui-tabs horizontal-tabs" data-aui-responsive=3D"true">
<strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data-conte=
nt-id=3D"1399050517">1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Introduction To API Testing</stron=
g>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"f71de043-c5ca-40ac-9033-c26e502b=
fe11-1399050517">
<p>In a distributed environment, the main challenge is dealing with many mo=
ving parts in the systems and subsystems. These parts are always changing, =
and multiple services interact with each other at the same time.</p>
<p>Imagine you're managing different teams that work on different areas of =
the systems and subsystems, and they deploy updates multiple times a day. I=
f you don't know what changes they made, it could cause problems if proper =
testing isn't done.</p>
<p>It gets really complicated, and if something goes wrong, fixing it can b=
e really difficult. Taking out one small part of the system can be hard bec=
ause other parts depend on it, and reversing those changes can be tricky. T=
hat's why it's really important to test the smaller parts of the system tho=
roughly.</p>
<h1 id=3D"id-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3IntroductionToAPITesting-TestPyramidforAppl=
icationwithMicroservicesarchitecture"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);">=
<strong>Test Pyramid for Application with Microservices architecture</stron=
g></span></h1>
<p><br></p>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image confluence-content-image-b=
order" draggable=3D"false" width=3D"468" src=3D"88d52421c8708bdc4dd7894aa46=
e6260928384878a53f99e19eea6012074463d" data-image-src=3D"/download/attachme=
nts/1399050517/image2023-5-31_15-56-32.png?version=3D1&amp;modificationDate=
=3D1685512592173&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-comment-count=3D"0" data-lin=
ked-resource-id=3D"1399053448" data-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-link=
ed-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"image=
2023-5-31_15-56-32.png" data-base-url=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com=
.au" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-linked-resource-c=
ontainer-id=3D"1399050517" data-linked-resource-container-version=3D"16" al=
t=3D"" height=3D"277"></span></p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"id-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3IntroductionToAPITesting-TypesofTestinginMi=
croservices"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Types of Testing =
in Microservices</strong></span></h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3IntroductionToAPITesting-UnitTests"><span s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Unit Tests</strong></span></h3>
<p><span>Unit Testing </span>is a type of software testing that allows you =
to check the accuracy of individual modules or software components. The goa=
l is to verify that each unit of code works correctly.</p>
<p>At the feature development stage, developers write unit tests independen=
tly because each developer knows and understands the workings of their code=
 better and can perform this task better than the testers.</p>
<p>Unit tests are written and run by developers in their local machine and =
during build pipeline.</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3IntroductionToAPITesting-ContractTests"><sp=
an style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Contract Tests</strong></span></h=
3>
<p>It is a test next to the unit test level, verifying that it meets the co=
ntract expected by consumer service.</p>
<p><span>Contract Testing </span>is a technique for testing an integration =
point by isolating each microservice and checking whether the communication=
 that the microservice transmits conform to a common understanding document=
ed in a contract.</p>
<p>In order to perform 'Consumer driver contract test', you need to simulat=
e its dependencies by replacing them with mocks.</p>
<p>Automated Contract tests can be scripted by both developers and quality =
engineers. It must be run on their local machine and through the Contract T=
esting pipeline against the latest updated code or Dev environment respecti=
vely.</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3IntroductionToAPITesting-ComponentTests(STT=
ests)"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Component Tests (ST Tes=
ts)</strong></span></h3>
<p>Component Testing (also called as System Testing) allows you to independ=
ently validate and evaluate the performance of each component of a microser=
vice application without integrating other services.</p>
<p>Generally, it is easier and faster to run component tests to evaluate mi=
croservices.</p>
<p>Idempotent Tests written by developers during the Dev phase is just a su=
bset of Component tests as these tests are repeatable and not dependent on =
downstreams.</p>
<p>In order to fully functional test your microservice component in isolati=
on, you need to simulate its dependencies by replacing them with test doubl=
es (mocks) and develop the complete functional API test suite.</p>
<p>Automated Component tests are scripted by quality engineers. It must&nbs=
p;be run on their local machine and through the Component Testing pipeline =
against Dev / ST environments.</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3IntroductionToAPITesting-IntegrationTests(S=
ITTests)"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Integration Tests (S=
IT Tests)</strong></span></h3>
<p>API Integration Testing (also called as System Integration Testing) veri=
fies the correct functionality and interaction of different components or s=
ervices through API. These tests are performed to ensure that the integrati=
on points such as API endpoints, data exchanges and communication protocols=
 work as intended and adhere to the expected behaviour.</p>
<p>Integration Tests are nothing but the extension of the Component Tests, =
typically reused and gets extended by orchestrating the chain of API calls.=
</p>
<p>Automated Integration Tests are written by quality engineers and to be r=
un on their local machine and through Testing pipeline against SIT environm=
ent.</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3IntroductionToAPITesting-Performance/LoadTe=
sting(SVPTests)"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Performance /=
 Load Testing (SVP Tests)</strong></span></h3>
<p>Microservice Performance and Load tests are essential to validate the pe=
rformance and reliability of individual microservices and to ensure that th=
ey can handle the expected workload without causing system slowdowns or fai=
lures.&nbsp; It helps in optimising and fine-tuning the microservice archit=
ecture for efficient and scalable performance.</p>
<p>Load tests are primarily non-functional and hence it sits outside the ty=
pical testing pyramid.&nbsp;</p>
<p>These tests are written by quality engineers or the SVP testers and to b=
e run on their local machine or dedicated performance testing virtual machi=
ne against SVP environment.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><br></p>
</div><strong style=3D"text-decoration: underline" class=3D"pageTitle" data=
-content-id=3D"1607281085">API Component Testing Guidelines</strong>
<div class=3D"tabs-pane active-pane" id=3D"f71de043-c5ca-40ac-9033-c26e502b=
fe11-1607281085">
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-IntendedAudienceforthisGuide:"><spa=
n style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Intended Audience for this Guide:<=
/strong></span></h1>
<p>Developer, Tester, Quality Engineer, Tech Lead</p>
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-UseCase:"><span style=3D"color: rgb=
(0,0,128);"><strong>Use Case:&nbsp;</strong></span></h1>
<p>A developer or tester needs to automate API tests for a component via Po=
stman</p>
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-BeforeyouStart:"><span style=3D"col=
or: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Before you Start:&nbsp;</strong></span></h1>
<ol>
<li>API Component must be created</li>
<li>API Contract design is complete</li>
<li>Component implementation to be in progress or complete</li>
<li>Access to Postman</li>
</ol>
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-PurposeofAPIComponentTests:"><span =
style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Purpose of API Component Tests:</str=
ong></span></h1>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">API Component tests to run automat=
ically as part of the deployment Bamboo pipeline to ensure the successful v=
alidation.</span></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-WhatisanAPIComponentTest:"><span st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>What is an API Component Test:</strong=
></span></h1>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);"><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34=
);">API Component test refers to the functional testing for all the api end=
points related to that component.</span></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);"><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34=
);">Component testing includes all HTTP Methods such as GET, POST, PUT, PAT=
CH, DELETE.&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);"><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34=
);">As these are functional testing, these tests highly depends on the test=
 data availability on each of the environment.&nbsp;</span></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);"><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34=
);">In order to reduce the data dependency with the dependent APIs and to i=
ncrease the functional coverage; dependent APIs can be mocked within the co=
debase repo using Mockoon <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/=
display/MESH/Testing+Microservices#f71de043-c5ca-40ac-9033-c26e502bfe11-155=
7945143" rel=3D"nofollow">API Virtualization in Mesh</a></span></span></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-TooltoAutomateAPITests:"><span styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Tool to Automate API Tests:</strong></sp=
an></h1>
<p>Open Source Version of Postman is used to script and test API endpoints.=
</p>
<h3 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-Teststobecommitted:"><span style=3D=
"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Tests to be committed:</strong></span></h3>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Component test collection file shoul=
d be named as 'component_tests_postman_collection.json' and it should be co=
mmitted in the same dev code base repository under the project root directo=
ry ./api-tests/default</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">If the test varies between environme=
nts then respective env folder to be created and seperate collection to be =
placed underneath.</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Default tests would run against all =
envs and tests under respective env folder would run only against those env=
ironments during deploy pipeline when custom run is triggered with ENABLE_C=
OMPONENT_TESTS variable set to True</span></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-Variation:"><span style=3D"color: r=
gb(0,0,128);"><strong>Variation</strong></span>:&nbsp;</h3>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Usage of Postman collection is recomm=
ended as default. However you are welcome to use other ATP approved tools e=
.g RestAssure to automate these api tests. Usage of different tools wont be=
 custom integrated with API deployment pipeline.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">You can set up the separate automated=
 test execution pipeline if required.</span></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-GuidelinesforcreatinggoodAPICompone=
ntTests:"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Guidelines for creat=
ing good API Component Tests:</strong></span></h1>
<ul>
<li>Create a collection and write Postman tests for all end points based on=
 the data dependency</li>
<li>If there is a downstream data dependency, mock the downstream apis via =
Mockoon&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/=
Testing+Microservices#f71de043-c5ca-40ac-9033-c26e502bfe11-1557945143" rel=
=3D"nofollow">API Service Virtualization in Mesh</a>
<ul>
<li>Endpoints in postman collection to have --&gt; x-systemTest Header set =
to true to redirect the downstreams to mockoon</li>
</ul></li>
<li>If the endpoint has mandatory query parameters, there should be a valid=
 test for that endpoint with required query parameters</li>
<li>If the endpoint has path parameters, then the test should have a valid =
endpoint with path parameter value (either as hard coded value or as a vari=
able)</li>
<li>Each test should follow with proper assertion statements.</li>
<li>Assertions should exist for both response status code and response mess=
age as well.</li>
<li>Assertions should follow appropriate pattern=20
<ul>
<li>e.g. responseCode.code <strong>=3D=3D=3D</strong> 200 and <strong><em>d=
o&nbsp;not&nbsp;use</em>&nbsp;</strong>responseCode.code<strong>&nbsp;!=3D=
=3D</strong> 500&nbsp;</li>
<li><p>Try to always assert with expected value.</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">Good Test Example</b><span class=3D"collapse-source=
 expand-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon=
 icon">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span=
></span><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Midnight; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Midnigh=
t">"script": {
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"exec": [
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"if (responseCode.code =3D=3D=3D 200) {\r",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"    tests[\"Status code is 200\"] =3D true;\r",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"    var jsonData =3D JSON.parse(responseBody);\=
r",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"    tests[\"Result is non-empty\"] =3D jsonData=
.data.idempotentTestCoverages.length =3D=3D=3D 0;\r",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"}\r",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"else {\r",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"    tests[\"expected at least one result for /i=
dempotentTestCoverages\"] =3D false;\r",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"}"
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09],
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"type": "text/javascript"
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09}</pre>
</div>
</div></li>
<li><p>&nbsp;<em><strong>!=3D=3D</strong> 500 <strong>would pass irrespecti=
ve of actual status code</strong> 200, 400, 401, 404 , etc.. and <strong>he=
nce this is considered as bad test</strong></em></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">Bad Test example</b><span class=3D"collapse-source =
expand-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon =
icon">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span>=
</span><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: Midnight; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Midnigh=
t">"script": {
=09=09=09=09=09=09"type": "text/javascript",
=09=09=09=09=09=09"exec": [
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"if(responseCode.code !=3D=3D 500){",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"tests[\"Status code is 200\"] =3D true;",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"var jsonData =3D JSON.parse(responseBody);",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"tests[\"Status is success\"] =3D (jsonData.status =3D=
=3D=3D \"success\") || (jsonData.type =3D=3D=3D \"ok\");",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"}",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"else{",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"    tests[\"Status Code is: \"+responseCode.code] =3D=
 false;",
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09"}"
=09=09=09=09=09=09]
=09=09=09=09=09}</pre>
</div>
</div></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Consider adding good assertions for the response data verification and =
not just the response code</li>
<li>Consider adding tests around some of the negative scenarios .&nbsp;=20
<ul>
<li>e.g. Invalid componentId - Expected to return 200 with empty string.&nb=
sp;</li>
<li>e.g. Missing Header - Expected to return 400 with valid error message</=
li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIComponentTestingGuidelines-MESHCONNECTPortaldisplaysOverallTes=
tScore"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>MESH CONNECT Portal di=
splays Overall Test Score</strong></span></h1>
<p><br></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Your Idempotent and non-idempotent Te=
st Coverage gets displayed in Mesh Connect against your component in Qualit=
y tab as below:</span></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image confluence-content-image-b=
