<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-IntendedAudienceforthisGuide:"><span styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Intended Audience for this Guide:</stron=
g></span></h1>
<p>Developer, Tester, Quality Engineer, Tech Lead</p>
<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-UseCase:"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,1=
28);"><strong>Use Case:&nbsp;</strong></span></h1>
<p>A developer or tester needs to test their API component in isolation.</p=
>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> <strong>Only applicable for Java API and Exp API =
components and not DotNet API at the moment</strong></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-BeforeyouStart:"><span style=3D"color: rg=
b(0,0,128);"><strong>Before you Start:&nbsp;</strong></span></h1>
<ol>
<li>API Component repository must be created</li>
<li>API design is completed</li>
<li>Component implementation to be started, in progress, or complete</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/Mesh+Deve=
loper+Tools" rel=3D"nofollow">Mesh Developer Tools</a> must be installed fo=
r local API testing</li>
</ol>
<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-Introduction"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0=
,0,128);"><strong>Introduction</strong></span></h1>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">API Virtualization is the process =
of using a tool that creates the copy of the api with all its specification=
s for testing purpose.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-PurposeofAPIVirtualization:"><span style=
=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Purpose of API Virtualization:</strong></=
span></h1>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">API Virtualization (Mocks) enables=
 development and testing teams to mock the dependent apis and test their co=
mponent in isolation, even when the dependent API is still being developed =
and not ready for consuming.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">As a component owner, you must tes=
t your component in isolation (Component testing) to ensure faster feedback=
 cycles and that defects are identified at the early stage to enable a shif=
t-left approach.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(23,43,77);">It also enables efficient Performa=
nce / Load testing for your api component in isolation.</span></p>
<h3 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-SCENARIO:"><strong><span style=3D"color: =
rgb(0,0,128);">SCENARIO:</span></strong></h3>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>GIVEN</strong> <span style=
=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">I am the API owner (developer or tester) of "X" =
</span></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>AND</strong> <span style=3D=
"color: rgb(0,51,102);">"X" is dependent on other api "Y"</span></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>WHEN</strong> <span style=
=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">I mock the endpoints of dependent component "Y"<=
/span></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>THEN</strong><span style=3D=
"color: rgb(0,51,102);"> I can test my component "X" in isolation without r=
elying on "Y" 's availability</span></span></p>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-ToolforAPIVirtualization:"><span style=3D=
"color: rgb(0,0,128);"><strong>Tool for API Virtualization:</strong></span>=
</h1>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">Westpac Mesh have chosen the open =
source tooling <em>Mockoon&nbsp;</em></span>to mock the APIs in Mesh for te=
sting</p>
<p>Mockoon is the easiest and quickest way to design and run your api mocks=
</p>
<ul>
<li>Get working mock REST APIs in seconds with an intuitive and easy-to-use=
 interface</li>
<li>Supports both Swagger and Openapi specification</li>
<li>Provides complete flexibility when creating mocks with custom statuses,=
 route, global headers, body editor etc</li>
<li>Simulates real-life scenarios with dynamic templating and the response =
rules system.</li>
<li>Proxy redirection support - intercepting the selected endpoints and for=
ward the rest to the defined proxy.</li>
<li>Run them anywhere anytime with the CLI support</li>
<li>Privacy friendly and offline first - Highly secured.</li>
</ul>
<p>Reference: <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://mockoon.com/" rel=
=3D"nofollow">https://mockoon.com/</a></p>
<p><br></p>
<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-Installation:"><span style=3D"color: rgb(=
0,0,128);"><strong>Installation:</strong></span></h1>
<p>Download mockoon GUI from here</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://mockoon.com/download/#download-section" class=3D"exte=
rnal-link" rel=3D"nofollow">https://mockoon.com/download/#download-section<=
/a></p>
<p>Old Version: 5.1.0</p>
<p>Windows: <a href=3D"https://github.com/mockoon/mockoon/releases/download=
/v5.1.0/mockoon.setup.5.1.0.exe" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">h=
ttps://github.com/mockoon/mockoon/releases/download/v5.1.0/mockoon.setup.5.=
1.0.exe</a>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Mac: <a href=3D"https://github.com/mockoon/mockoon/releases/download/v5.=
1.0/mockoon.setup.5.1.0.universal.dmg" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofol=
low">https://github.com/mockoon/mockoon/releases/download/v5.1.0/mockoon.se=
tup.5.1.0.universal.dmg</a></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Latest Version: 8.0.0 - Use this version if you are starting fre=
sh with mockoon or intend to migrate from 5.1.0 to latest&nbsp;</strong></p=
>
<p>Windows: <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"https://github.com/mockoon/m=
ockoon/releases/download/v8.0.0/mockoon.setup.8.0.0.exe" rel=3D"nofollow">h=
ttps://github.com/mockoon/mockoon/releases/download/v8.0.0/mockoon.setup.8.=
0.0.exe</a>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Mac: <a href=3D"https://github.com/mockoon/mockoon/releases/download/v=
=3D8.0.0/mockoon.setup.8.0.0.universal.dmg" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"=
nofollow">https://github.com/mockoon/mockoon/releases/download/v8.0.0/mocko=
on.setup.8.0.0.universal.dmg</a></p>
<p>Install via choco: choco install mockoon</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Note: With Platform 2.18 Release =E2=80=93 Mockoon version is up=
graded to 8.0.0. MOCKOON_CONTAINER_VERSION version 34. By default deploymen=
t uses this latest version. However if your mockoon_data.json is still not =
ready with latest version (there might be potential breakage if you were us=
ing rules in your mocks before) - you can do custom deployment run by point=
ing MOCKOON_CONTAINER_VERSION to 27 (this container version points to old m=
ockoon version 5.1).&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><strong>You can find the release notes for Mockoon 8.0.0 here <a href=3D=
"https://mockoon.com/releases/8.0.0/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofoll=
ow">https://mockoon.com/releases/8.0.0/</a> for reference</strong></p>
<p><br></p>
