<h1 id=3D"APIVirtualizationinMesh-Glossary:"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,=
128);"><strong>Glossary:</strong></span></h1>
<p><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/MESH/Glossary+f=
or+How+to+Guides" rel=3D"nofollow">Glossary for How to Guides</a></p>
<p><br></p>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro confluence-information-macro-not=
e">
<p class=3D"title conf-macro-render">Troubleshooting</p><span class=3D"aui-=
icon aui-icon-small aui-iconfont-warning confluence-information-macro-icon"=
></span>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro-body">
<p><br></p>
<ol>
<li>Mockoon mocks are created in local but downstream calls are not getting=
 redirected to mockoon in local:=20
<ol>
<li>This might not be issue with mockoon directly. First make sure if your =
api (if dependent apis are already deployed to environment) works as expect=
ed in the environment. Sometimes the downstream connection itself might be =
a issue which need to be addressed first.</li>
<li>E.G: APIs using WDPRestTemplate but having Async calls wont work proper=
ly with redirection because of which mockoon redirection wont work as well.=
 Please note: Async to be used only with WDPWebClient and not WDPRestTempla=
te.</li>
<li>It might be due to explicit setting of hostname in your Uribuilder. As =
WDPHelper sets the hostname on its own based on your app config, you should=
 not be setting this explicitly while building the Uri.&nbsp;</li>
<li>It could be due to explicit header settings in your code. As WDPHelper =
sets the header, you should not be setting the headers explicitly. If you a=
re setting the header due to JWT auth - then x-systemTest header to be fetc=
hed from the httpHeaders and passed on explicitly in your code too.</li>
</ol></li>
<li>Mockoon integrated with api in local and working as expected in local. =
But not working in the environment after deployment=20
<ol>
<li>For dev1 environment - by default ENABLE_COMPONENT_TESTS is true. For o=
ther non prod environments - by default it is false. If mockoon to be enabl=
ed custom deployment run with ENABLE_COMPONENT_TESTS set to true should be =
done</li>
<li>If that still doesnt work , your mock file might not have been compatib=
le with mockoon server in test container.</li>
<li><strong>With Platform 2.18 Release =E2=80=93 Mockoon version is upgrade=
d to 8.0.0. MOCKOON_CONTAINER_VERSION version 34. By default deployment use=
s this latest version. However if your mockoon_data.json is still not ready=
 with latest version (there might be potential breakage if you were using r=
ules in your mocks before) - you can do custom deployment run by pointing M=
OCKOON_CONTAINER_VERSION to 27 (this container version points to old mockoo=
n version 5.1).&nbsp;</strong></li>
</ol></li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
